  1. Conduct an indirect ordination on the dune plant community. Specifically, visually examine a NMDS plot using the bray-curtis distance metric. Below is some code to help you develop a potential plot that emphasizes the role of the environmental variable Moisture. Describe how you interpret the graphic. What is the goal of creating such a plot? Does this analysis suggest any interesting findings with respect to the dune vegetation?
#make the nmds model 
#remember: 
  #NMDS Maximizes rank-order correlation between distance measures and distance in ordination        #space. Points are moved to minimize stress. Stress is a measure of the mismatch between the     #two kinds of distance indirect, so only a single matrix is analyzed
  #bray-curtis is default distance metric
dune_mds <- metaMDS(dune, distance = "bray")

```r
plot(dune_mds, type='n')
text(dune_mds, 'sp', cex=.5)
# generate vector of colors 
color_vect = rev(terrain.colors(6))[-1]
points(dune_mds, 'sites', pch=19, 
       col=color_vect[dune.env$Moisture])
legend('topright', paste("Moisture =", 1:5, sep=''), 
       col=color_vect, pch=19)
```

<img src="multivariate_hw_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-3-1.png" width="672" />

How to interpret the graphic: The axes on this plot are meaningless. The distance between points represents the similarity or dissimilarity between points (plant species) for the metric observed (moisture). Points that are closer together have similar moisture requirements than points far from each other.

Goal of creating plot: To observe similarities and differences in moisture requirements for dune species in a two dimensional space.

Findings with respect to dune vegetation: There are two distinct clusters of points, indicating that there are two distinct groups of vegetation that have similar moisture requirements with a healthy spectrum of species between them. It appears as though airaprae, empenigr, and hyporadi are outliers and the model might be improved by throwing out those data points.

  1. Carry out a direct ordination using CCA in order to test any potential hypotheses that you developed after examining the MDS plot. Specifically, carry out a test of the entire model (i.e., including all constrained axes) and also carry out tests at the scale of individual explanatory variables you included in your model if you included more than one variable. Plot your results.
#test of entire model
  #remember: variables are A1 (measure of soil thickness), moisture, management, use, and manure
cca_dune <- cca(dune ~ ., data=dune.env)
RsquareAdj(cca_dune, 100)
## $r.squared
## [1] 0.7106267
## 
## $adj.r.squared
## [1] 0.223874
anova(cca_dune, permutations = 999)

  1. Do your two analyses agree with one another or complement one another or do these two analyses seem to be suggesting different take home messages? Which analysis do you find to be more useful?

The two analyses agree with one another. It would appear as though both analyses agree that there are distinct groups of vegetation that cluster around certain moisture levels. However, CCA makes it more apparent that there are other variables that are significant, such as A1 (p=0.027), Management (p < 0.001) and Manure (p=0.027); but not Use (p=0.27) . I find CCA to be more useful because of this as well as the length of the arrows, which denote the strength of the correlation. Additionally, the direction of the arrows indicates positive or negative correlations between points. Based on this analysis, it seems that many dune species are tolerant of different levels of moisture, thereby maintaining their specific niche within the ecosystem.
